[SourceTitle "01 Rubinstein System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "nimzo-indian-defense-tournament-edition/course/2359, variation/78873"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. Nf3 {This is the main 
line.} c5 {Black puts more pawns in the center.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3 Bxc3 9. bxc3 
dxc4 {Black releases some of the pawn tension.} 10. Bxc4 Qc7 {Here White has 
almost 10 valid options, but they are all met with the same move.} 11. Bb2 e5 
{Black breaks up White's pawn center.} 12. h3 Bf5 13. Qe2 Rad8 {This type of 
position can be reached with slightly different development by White, but the 
ideas remain the same. Black does NOT want to take on d4 with his pawns unless 
he wins material. The reason is that opening lines in the center would activate 
White's bishop pair, which would benefit from an open position. Instead, Black 
puts his rooks on the e and d-files and puts pressure on White's center.} *

