1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 7. Bg5 Bb7 8. e3 
{This is a more principled approach. White does not take away the f3 square from 
his knight.} d6 {Black achieves a very flexible pawn structure with ideas of 
preparing c5, d5, or e5. Black can adjust his plans based on personal 
preferences or how White develops. Here is one possible line.} 9. f3 Nbd7 10. 
Bd3 c5 11. Ne2 Rc8 {Black has good play.} *

