1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 7. Nf3 {White 
can also develop the knight before playing Bg5.} Bb7 8. e3 {Bg5 would transpose 
to flexible structures explored in previously mentioned variations after d6.} d6 
9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O Ne4 {Black attacks the queen and brings his knight to the 
center.} 11. Qc2 f5 12. b4 {White seeks counterplay on the queenside.} Rf6 {This 
is a typical maneuver in lines where the knight is on e4 and the f-pawn on f5. 
Black seeks attacking chances on the kingside.} *

