[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "nimzo-indian-defense-tournament-edition/course/2359, variation/78834"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 {This move has enjoyed a rise in popularity 
recently. It is a very natural move, developing the knight to f3.} b6 {d5 is 
also a very good choice, but it transposes to the Ragozin Variation of the 
Queen's Gambit Declined.} 5. Bg5 Bb7 6. e3 {This is the main line.} h6 7. Bh4 
{Here Black can choose from two eqally popular options: Bxc3+ and g5. I prefer 
the more aggressive g5 line.} g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. Qc2 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 {If White 
tries to get rid of the knight on e4 by playing Nd2, Black can simply take on g3 
with a good position.} 11. Bd3 {If White tries to get rid of the knight on e4 by 
playing Nd2, Black can simply take on g3 with a good position.} f5 12. d5 Nd7 
{Black's structure is has some similarities with that of a Dutch Defense.} 13. 
Bxe4 fxe4 14. Qxe4 Qf6 15. O-O O-O-O 16. Qxe6 Qxe6 17. dxe6 Nc5 {Black has an 
excellent position.} *

