[SourceTitle "05 Leningrad Variation"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "nimzo-indian-defense-tournament-edition/course/2359, variation/78815"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {This is known as the Leningrad Variation.} 
c5 5. d5 h6 6. Bh4 {Taking on f6 gives Black excellent winning chances after a 
simple Queen recapture.} Bxc3+ {Douling White's pawns.} 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3 e5 
{This very solid structure arises often in the Leningrad Variation. Notice that 
Black is left with a light-squared bishop, but his pawns are fixed on the dark 
squares. This works in his favor because his bishop is not stuck behind his own 
pawns.} *

