1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 {This sideline is a favorite of players who 
are addicted to fianchetto systems. In general however, White cannot hope for 
much of an advantage.} c5 {This is the main line. The moves d5 or simply 
castling are also playable.} 5. Nf3 {White lends extra support to his d4 pawn.} 
cxd4 6. Nxd4 O-O 7. Bg2 d5 {Now White has three different options.} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 
9. Qb3 {If Bd2 instead, Black should damage White's pawn structure with Bxc3.} 
Nc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. O-O Qa5 12. Bd2 Bxc3 13. bxc3 {White wants to keep his 
bishop pair.} Ba6 {The following line is very theoretical.} 14. Rfd1 Qc5 15. e4 
Bc4 16. Qa4 Nb6 17. Qb4 Qh5 {Black has a decent game.} *

